:::summary
Psychology is the scientific study of mind, behavior, and human experience — investigating perception, cognition, emotion, memory, motivation, personality, and mental health. Though it emerged as an independent experimental discipline only in the late nineteenth century, questions about the soul, human nature, and the causes of behavior have occupied philosophers and theologians for millennia. The Christian tradition insists that human beings are not reducible to matter or conditioning alone but are ensouled creatures made in the image of God (*imago Dei*), a conviction that shapes a rich dialogue between psychology and Christian thought.
:::

